Posted @withregram • @yellowstudiony Yellow Studio Member Spotlight on Julie Rosenberg ✨ A Katonah-based artist, musician and all around awesome friend and person. @julierosenbergguitar 

1. Why did you join YS?

I joined YS to support the vision of Tina, my friend and fellow KMAA Advisory Board Member. When Tina first described her plan to me, which was to establish a hub for women artists, entrepreneurs, and the like, to gather, learn from and inspire one another, I knew that I wanted to support this kind of integrity and vision. I am a fan of a start-ups, and of women pioneers who take the lead in fields where a new working model or brand, approach or style has the potential to offer great benefit to individual clients and the surrounding community.

2. What has been your favorite YS memory so far?

My favorite memory, so far, is the first time I walked in. It was early on. The space had not yet been transformed into the vibrant environment it is today. As we walked the rooms, Tina
described how raw walls would soon fill with artwork, tables and chairs would support work areas and empty corners of rooms would couch social interactions. Listening to Tina articulate and gesture her mind’s vision, sensing the excitement and rawness in the moment, I recognized
the entrepreneurial spirit coming to life. I was in.

3. What do you like to do for fun?

I enjoy playing music with friends, and playing in gigs. Katonah and its nearby towns have a handful of local restaurants and art venues that support our local musicians by offering live music at their events and YS is one of them! I love to get out & see my friends perform with their bands and attend art shows. I enjoy relaxing in any downtime, playing with my dog, spending quality time with my partner, friends & family and of course, painting guitars!

4. Where do your professional interests lie? 

I paint and design electric guitars that are sold to recreational & professional guitar players. This is what I love to do. My guitar business stems from being a guitarist & artist my entire life. I am very involved in our local art & music scenes and currently serve as President of the Katonah Museum Artists’ Association.

The “OG-2” body held up very well since I painted it c.1988. I am excited that it is now a rockin’ guitar that holds its own, and then some. I had a chance to play it at a gig, recently. Sounds and feels fantastic. Kept to its original routed configuration, which was drilled for one control. I went with a volume knob to to adjust the one pickup on board. The single coil cavity was a bit tight and I didn’t want to do any modification to this body. I chose a DiMarzio Evolution, Bridge HB and it seals the deal. The four predrilled pickup rings nicely accommodated a new ring. The Floyd Rose Rail Tail Tremolo  bridge is a perfect fit. Complete with a set of LaBella Strings, 10-gauge.

I was reminded yesterday in an interview I had with a lovely woman for her podcast that much of my inspiration in my art work comes from architecture and design. Watching my mom, design homes and their interior spaces allowed me to appreciate space and the elements within, in three dimensional terms. When I look at a guitar body or pickguard that I’m about to paint, I conceptualize the overall design in three dimensional terms, as if it’s a room. It’s not just about visual art for me, it’s also about art in terms of sculpture. Industry. Functionality. Building. Engineering. In one hand is a paint brush in the other hand is another tool. That is the hands-on application. But the relationship of elements that I will bring onto the canvas is about the relationships that each element has to one another. The overall plan/design has to hang together. The whole instrument will also reflect that principal. Form follows function. Thanks, mom for modeling that kind of thinking and doing. It will always stick with me ❤️ @dyanrosenberg
